ERD is a web-based tool developed by SoC’s Prof. Adi Yoga S. Prabawa for drawing ER diagrams.

The ERD tool takes as input a ER diagram specification (or ERD specification) and translates it into a lower level specification (using the dot language) which is then processed using one of the dot language processors to generate an output ER diagram image file. dot is a graph description language developed at AT&T Bell Labs in the 80’s.

The purpose of this document is teach you how to use the ERD specification language and how to use the ERD tool to generate an ER diagram image file from an input ERD specification.

1. ERD Tool

The figure below shows the web-based interface of the ERD tool which consists of three panels. The top left panel is the input panel which is a text area for typing/editing your ERD specification. The right panel is the output panel which displays the ER diagram generated from the input ERD specification. Finally, the bottom left panel is the status panel which is a text area for displaying error messages.

There are two ways to input a ERD specification using the ERD tool. The first way is to type the specification using the input panel. The second way is to load a ERD specification file by clicking the Browse button; the loaded specification file will be displayed in the input panel.

To generate a ER diagram from the ERD specification, you need to perform two steps. The first step is to select one of the seven available dot language processors (dot, neato, twopi, circo, fdp, osage, sfdp) to process the dot specification that is translated from the input ERD specification. These dot language processors use different heuristics to optimize the layout of the generated ER diagram. The default processor is dot. You can choose a different processor by clicking on the selector besides the Browse button to pick from a menu of the seven options.

The second step is to click on the wheel icon to enumerate through the different ER diagram layouts that are produced by the selected processor. Some of the processors may have only one possible layout generated. You can try out different processors and their layouts to select your preferred ER diagram layout.

To save the generated ER diagram layout into a PNG image file, click on the rightmost image icon to save it into a file named ERD.png.

For advanced users who are familiar with the dot language, you can save dot specification of the generated ER diagram layout by clicking on the file icon (to the right of the wheel icon) to make further customizations to the dot specification. The dot specification file can be processed using any of the dot processors (by installing graphviz software) to generate an image file.

2. ERD Specification Language

This section presents the ERD specification language by using examples of ER diagrams from Lecture 4 and Tutorial 3.

A ERD specification consists of a sequence of one or more statements (the order of the statements does not matter). Each statement specifies one of the following six ER Diagram constructs and must terminate with a semicolon:

  • An entity set is specified by the entity name (enclosed by square brackets) followed by the list of its attributes (enclosed by parentheses and separated by commas). An attribute that forms part of the primary key has a "*" added to the end of the attribute name. The order of the attributes does not matter.

  • A relationship set is specified similarly as an entity set except that the relationship name is enclosed by angle brackets. Note that the parentheses "()" must be specified even if the relationship set has no attributes.

  • A relationship edge is specified in terms of four components:

    • the entity/aggregation name

    • the relationship edge annotation (to be described later)

    • the relationship name

    • an optional rolename (enclosed by square brackets)

  • A weak entity set is specified similar to a regular entity set except that the entity name is enclosed by double square brackets and the name of its identifying relationship set is enclosed by double angle brackets.

  • A relationship set that is also an aggregation is specified similar to a regular relationship set except that the name of the relationship is enclosed by angle brackets followed by square brackets (e.g., [<Sponsors>]).

  • A ISA hierarchy is specified in terms of three components:

    • the superclass entity name

    • the ISA hierarchy edge annotation (to be described later)

    • the set of subclass entity names (enclosed by curly braces and separated by commas). Note that the order of the subclass names does not matter.

There are four options for a relationship edge annotation for an entity/aggregation named E that is participant in a relationship named R:

  • If the participation of E wrt R is partial without any key constraint, the edge annotation is ---

  • If the participation of E wrt R is partial with a key constraint on E wrt R, the edge annotation is -→

  • If the participation of E wrt R is total without any key constraint, the edge annotation is ===

  • If the participation of E wrt R is total with a key constraint on E wrt R, the edge annotation is =⇒

There are four options for a ISA hierarchy edge annotation:

  • If it satisfies the overlap constraint but not the covering constraint, the edge annotation is ---

  • If it satisfies both the overlap & covering constraints, the edge annotation is ===

  • If it satisfies neither the overlap nor covering constraint, the edge annotation is -→

  • If it does not satisfy the overlap constraint but satisfies the covering constraint, the edge annotation is =⇒

2.1. Example 1: Many-to-Many Relationship (Lecture 4, Slide 18)

[Students](sid*, name, dob);
[Courses](cid*, cname, credits);
<Enrolls>(year*, semester*, grade);
Students --- Enrolls;
Courses --- Enrolls;

2.2. Example 2: Relationship Role (Lecture 4, Slide 13)

[Students](sid*, name, dob);
<Mentors>();
Students --- Mentors [senior];
Students --- Mentors [junior];

2.3. Example 3: Key Constraint (Lecture 4, Slide 21)

[Profs](pid*, name, room);
[Students](sid*, name, dob);
<Supervises>(since);
Profs --- Supervises;
Students --> Supervises;

2.4. Example 4: Total Participation Constraint (Lecture 4, Slide 27)

[Students](sid*, name, dob);
[Courses](cid*, cname, credits);
<Enrolls>(grade);
Students === Enrolls;
Courses --- Enrolls;

2.5. Example 5: Key & Total Participation Constraint (Lecture 4, Slide 30)

[Students](sid*, name, dob);
[Courses](cid*, cname, credits);
<Enrolls>(grade);
Students ==> Enrolls;
Courses --- Enrolls;

2.6. Example 6: Weak Entity Set (Lecture 4, Slide 31)

[Books](isbn*, title, author);
[[Chapters]](number*, title);
<<Contains>>();
Books --- Contains;
Chapters ==> Contains;

2.7. Example 7: Aggregation (Lecture 4, Slide 48)

[Projects](pid*, startedOn);
[Departments](did*, dname);
[Employees](eid*, ename);
[<Sponsors>](since);
Projects === Sponsors;
Departments --- Sponsors;
<Monitors>(until);
Employees --- Monitors;
Sponsors --- Monitors;

2.8. Example 8: Aggregation (Tutorial 3, Q2a)

[A](a1*, a2);
[B](b1*, b2);
[C](c1*, c2);
[D](d1*, d2);
[<R>](r1);
A --- R;
B --- R;
[<S>](s1);
C --- S;
R --- S;
<T>(t1);
D --- T;
S --- T;

2.9. Example 9: ISA Hierarchy (Lecture 4, Slide 52)

[Students](sid*, name);
[Ugrads](satScore);
[Grads](bachelorDegree);
[Offices](rid*,phone,location);
<Works>();
Grads --- Works;
Offices --- Works;
Students ==> {Ugrads, Grads};

2.10. Example 10: ISA Hierarchy (Tutorial 3, Q2b)

[A](a1*,a2);
[B](b1);
[C](c1);
[D](d1);
[E](e1);
[F](f1);
A --- {B,C};
B --- {D};
C --> {D,E,F};

2.11. Example 11: Tutorial 3, Q3

[Patients](ssn*, name, age, address);
[Doctors](ssn*, name, speciality, years);
[Pharmacies](address*);
[PharmaceuticalCompanies](name*, phone, address);
[Drugs](tradeName*, formula);
<PrimaryPhysician>();
<Prescribes>(date, qty);
<Sells>(price);
<Contracts>(startDate, endDate, text);
<Makes>();
Patients --- PrimaryPhysician;
Doctors --- PrimaryPhysician;
Doctors --- Prescribes;
Drugs --- Prescribes;
Pharmacies --- Sells;
Drugs --- Sells;
Pharmacies --- Contracts;
PharmaceuticalCompanies --- Contracts;
Drugs --- Makes;
PharmaceuticalCompanies --- Makes;
